WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.000
And if you've got a Bible, I would invite you to turn with me to John chapter 11.

2
00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:09.000
So John chapter 11.

3
00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:13.000
It's also found there in your worship guides.

4
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:18.000
But as you're turning there, maybe go in your mind's eye to the airport.

5
00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:22.000
I'm sure there's places you'd rather be than the airport today.

6
00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:25.000
But you are heading there for your flight.

7
00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:29.000
You're running a little bit late, but you get there just in time to check in your bags.

8
00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:32.000
And you get through security.

9
00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:36.000
And as you're huffing and puffing, you run up to the screen that says departures,

10
00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:38.000
and you find your flight.

11
00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:44.000
And right beside it, you read that dreaded word in red, delayed.

12
00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:48.000
And you just can't help but groan as you see that word delayed.

13
00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:52.000
About a month ago, my brother came to visit.

14
00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:54.000
And it was great to see him.

15
00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:56.000
This happened to him.

16
00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:00.000
He was flying to Alabama, got stopped in Denver, and his flight was delayed.

17
00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:03.000
But you may remember that day, not because you necessarily know him,

18
00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:07.000
but because it was the day that most of us were hunkered down in a basement somewhere

19
00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:11.000
because we were waiting on a tornado to arrive, or listening to James Spann

20
00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:13.000
and keeping our eye on the weather.

21
00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:18.000
That was why his flight was delayed, because there's no way you should be flying in weather like that.

22
00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:23.000
So there was a delay, but it was for his good.

23
00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:29.000
Well, John chapter 11 begins with a delay that was much more disappointing.

24
00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:33.000
But it was also for a much greater good.

25
00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:37.000
Word has come to Jesus that his friend Lazarus is sick,

26
00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:41.000
and it looks like he is not going to pull through.

27
00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:45.000
Lazarus' sisters, Mary and Martha, are the ones who have sent word to him.

28
00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:50.000
And they've gotten in touch with Jesus not just to inform him about what is happening,

29
00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:55.000
and not just to kind of invite him to come and pay his last respects,

30
00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:59.000
but rather they get in touch with him because they want him to heal Lazarus.

31
00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:02.000
They had seen him heal total strangers.

32
00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:07.000
Surely he would heal his friend whom he loved.

33
00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:10.000
But then the text says something very puzzling.

34
00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:16.000
It says, he loved them, Lazarus, Mary and Martha.

35
00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:24.000
So when he heard that Lazarus was ill, he stayed two days longer where he was.

36
00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:27.000
Now you might expect it to say something like, he heard he was ill,

37
00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:32.000
so he arose immediately and went to his friend Lazarus and healed him.

38
00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:34.000
But that's not what it says.

39
00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:38.000
It says he delayed two days.

40
00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:43.000
Then when Jesus finally turns up, Lazarus is dead.

41
00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:49.000
Now you can imagine the disappointment of Mary and Martha when Jesus arrives.

42
00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:53.000
They were going through such a painful time.

43
00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:58.000
And now they see Jesus and you can imagine the disappointment they must have felt.

44
00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:02.000
But from our perspective we can see that this delay was for a much greater good.

45
00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:11.000
So follow along with me now as we read this passage beginning where Jesus arrives in John 11 and verse 17.

46
00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:17.000
It says, now when Jesus came, he found that Lazarus had already been dead in the tomb four days.

47
00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:22.000
Bethany was near Jerusalem about two miles off.

48
00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:28.000
And many of the Jews had come to Martha and Mary to console them concerning their brother.

49
00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:33.000
So when Martha heard that Jesus was coming, she went and met him.

50
00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:36.000
But Mary remained seated in the house.

51
00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:40.000
Martha said to Jesus, Lord, if you had been here,

52
00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:43.000
my brother would not have died.

53
00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:48.000
But even now I know that whatever you ask from God, God will give you.

54
00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:52.000
Jesus said to her, your brother will rise again.

55
00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:58.000
Martha said to him, I know that he will rise again in the resurrection on the last day.

56
00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:04.000
Jesus said to her, I am the resurrection and the life.

57
00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:08.000
Whoever believes in me, though he died, yet shall he live.

58
00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:12.000
And everyone who lives and believes in me shall never die.

59
00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:14.000
Do you believe this?

60
00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:21.000
She said to him, Yes, Lord, I believe that you are the Christ, the Son of God who is coming into the world.

61
00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:25.000
When she had said this, she went and called her sister Mary saying in private,

62
00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:28.000
the teacher is here and is calling for you.

63
00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:32.000
And when she heard it, she rose quickly and went to him.

64
00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:38.000
Jesus had not yet come into the village, but was still in the place where Martha had met him.

65
00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:44.000
When the Jews who were with her in the house, consoling her, saw Mary rise quickly and go out,

66
00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:50.000
they followed her, supposing that she was going to the tomb to weep there.

67
00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:55.000
Now when Mary came to where Jesus was and saw him, she fell at his feet, saying to him,

68
00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:59.000
Lord, if you had been here, my brother would not have died.

69
00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:04.000
When Jesus saw her weeping and the Jews who had come with her also weeping,

70
00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:08.000
he was deeply moved in his spirit and greatly troubled.

71
00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:11.000
And he said, Where have you laid him?

72
00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:16.000
They said to him, Lord, come and see. Jesus wept.

73
00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:20.000
So the Jews said, See how he loved him.

74
00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:27.000
But some of them said, Could not he who opened the eyes of the blind also have kept this man from dying?

75
00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:31.000
Then Jesus deeply moved again, came to the tomb.

76
00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:34.000
It was a cave and a stone lay against it.

77
00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:37.000
Jesus said, Take away the stone.

78
00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:44.000
Martha, the sister of the dead man, said to him, Lord, by this time there will be an odor for he has been dead four days.

79
00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:51.000
Jesus said to her, Didn't I not tell you that if you believed you would see the glory of God?

80
00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:53.000
So they took away the stone.

81
00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:58.000
Jesus lifted up his eyes and said, Father, I thank you that you have heard me.

82
00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:07.000
I knew that you always hear me, but I said this on account of the people standing around that they may believe that you sent me.

83
00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:11.000
When he had said these things, he cried out with a loud voice.

84
00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:14.000
Lazarus, come out.

85
00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:17.000
The man who had died came out.

86
00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:22.000
His hands and feet bound with linen strips and his face wrapped with a cloth.

87
00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:26.000
Jesus said to them, unbind him and let him go.

88
00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:29.000
This is the word of the Lord.

89
00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:31.000
Let's pray.

90
00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:34.000
Lord, your word is powerful.

91
00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:37.000
You speak and the dead are raised to life.

92
00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:43.000
Lord, I pray that you would speak to us this morning and that your words would change us.

93
00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:45.000
Pray this in Jesus mighty name.

94
00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:48.000
Amen.

95
00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:53.000
I know all of us know what it is like to suffer in one way or another.

96
00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:59.000
We can easily identify with Mary and Martha here in the loss of their brother.

97
00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:04.000
And perhaps you can also identify with their disappointment.

98
00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:09.000
You know what it's like to ask Jesus for help, to ask him for healing.

99
00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:14.000
You prayed and you prayed, but nothing seemed to happen.

100
00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:17.000
And so you wonder, is he even there?

101
00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:24.000
Or maybe if he's there and he loves us, why doesn't he do something?

102
00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:31.000
Our passage this morning shows us that even when we do not know what God is doing

103
00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:38.000
or why he is delaying, we can still know that he is motivated by love

104
00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:41.000
in what he is doing for us.

105
00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:45.000
We may not be able to see his hand, but we can trust his heart.

106
00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:49.000
We can know that even though we do not understand what is going on,

107
00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:55.000
we can know that he loves us and is at work for the good of his friends.

108
00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:00.000
So in our passage, we see four assurances of Jesus' love.

109
00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:03.000
So I want us to just look at those four things together.

110
00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:05.000
We see Jesus' love in this.

111
00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:09.000
One, he came despite the threat.

112
00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:13.000
All right, so while those with Lazarus wondered why Jesus was delaying,

113
00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:18.000
those with Jesus were actually wondering why he went in the first place.

114
00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:24.000
In the passage just before what we actually have in our reading, in our worship guides,

115
00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:28.000
you see that the disciples are confused as to why Jesus would go.

116
00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:32.000
You see, there had been attempts on his life, multiple attempts on his life,

117
00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:34.000
in that very region recently.

118
00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:36.000
It was dangerous to go.

119
00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:41.000
So Jesus says, let us go to Judea again and they cannot believe it.

120
00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:45.000
They say, Rabbi, the Jews were just now seeking to stone you.

121
00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:47.000
Are you going to go there again?

122
00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:49.000
In other words, what are you thinking?

123
00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:54.000
You do not understand that your life is being threatened.

124
00:08:54.000 --> 00:09:01.000
After all those things transpire, we're told that it was then at this point,

125
00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:04.000
after the healing of Lazarus that we just read about,

126
00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:07.000
that the plans were made, definite plans to put Jesus to death.

127
00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:12.000
So what goes on here leads right to the cross.

128
00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:15.000
So where he was going was incredibly dangerous.

129
00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:18.000
He knew that and yet he went.

130
00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:21.000
You know, heroes are often described as those people who,

131
00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:25.000
when other people are running away from danger, they are running towards the danger.

132
00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:31.000
If you think of like 9-11, when everybody is running away from the Twin Towers,

133
00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:35.000
you look back to think about first responders, the policemen and the firefighters

134
00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:43.000
who are running in the direction of the towers to rescue as many people as they can.

135
00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:47.000
Why does Jesus go back to this place where he knows his life is under threat?

136
00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:50.000
Because he loves us.

137
00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:54.000
He's going so that we might be saved.

138
00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:57.000
This was true for this family here in the raising of Lazarus,

139
00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:00.000
but it is also true for us as well.

140
00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:04.000
He knew that going to Lazarus would mean ultimately going to the cross.

141
00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:08.000
Why does he go into the cross and suffer the cause?

142
00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:13.000
He loves us and he was prepared to die for us.

143
00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:19.000
So if his delay in whatever it is that you are longing for causes you to doubt his love,

144
00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:21.000
look at the cross.

145
00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:24.000
That's how much he loves you.

146
00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:28.000
So he came despite the threat, but he also came secondly,

147
00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.000
speaking the truth.

148
00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:32.000
In love, he speaks the truth.

149
00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:37.000
So we read that when he arrived in Bethany, Martha went out to meet him.

150
00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:40.000
When she got to him, she expressed her disappointment.

151
00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:41.000
Do you remember what she said?

152
00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:46.000
She said, Lord, if you had been here, my brother would not have died.

153
00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:53.000
And I'm amazed though that her disappointment is still mingled with a kind of dogged, persistent faith.

154
00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:59.000
But even now I know that whatever you ask of God, he will give it to you.

155
00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:04.000
So before I move on, could I just say that what Martha says here is just a beautiful example of prayer.

156
00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:11.000
She speaks to the Lord with this raw honesty expressing exactly what she is feeling.

157
00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:13.000
She's expressing her hurt to him.

158
00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:20.000
And yet she is calling out to him with persistent yet imperfect faith.

159
00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:22.000
So how does Jesus respond?

160
00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:26.000
Well, he responds by telling her a truth that she needs to hear.

161
00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:30.000
He tells her a truth that grounds her.

162
00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:36.000
I don't know if you've ever seen the Hunger Games movies or you've read the novels.

163
00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:41.000
I don't know if you're expecting to hear about Hunger Games on a day celebrating resurrection in life.

164
00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:49.000
But in the third one of the novels, Mockingjay, there's a character called Peta who's been taken away by the enemy, essentially.

165
00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:56.000
And he's been brainwashed and he's got a really loose grip on reality and it's scary.

166
00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:00.000
But now he's back with people who are friends of his.

167
00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:06.000
And it's hard to know for him what is real, what's a real memory, what's a false memory.

168
00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:12.000
And so his friends come up with a kind of a game, if you will, that helps him to see what reality is.

169
00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:17.000
When he's in doubt, he just says these words, real or not real.

170
00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:21.000
He'll say something that say real or not real and they'll say real or they'll say not real.

171
00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:29.000
And it ultimately leads to a point when his friend Katniss, when he says to her, you love me, real or not real.

172
00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:31.000
And she answers real.

173
00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:38.000
But here Jesus is assuring Martha of his love by giving her some reality to be grounded in.

174
00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:44.000
When he says what he says to her, he isn't kind of offering her a band-aid on her like gaping wound.

175
00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:48.000
Like thinking that's going to instantly make it better just by hearing the truth.

176
00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:54.000
No, but he is giving her solid ground to put her feet on when everything else is giving way around her.

177
00:12:54.000 --> 00:13:00.000
He's putting down an anchor, if you will, in the midst of the storm, in the fog and confusion of grief.

178
00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:06.000
He looks at her and he says real.

179
00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:11.000
We live in a confusing world and our feelings are such unreliable guides.

180
00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:15.000
And we need truth from outside of ourselves to ground us in reality.

181
00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:20.000
And the truth that we need more than anything else is what Jesus says to Martha.

182
00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.000
So what is it?

183
00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:27.000
Well, it begins by saying your brother will rise again in verse 23.

184
00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:31.000
And she thinks he's just speaking about a resurrection kind of at the end of time.

185
00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:35.000
But that's not what he's talking about.

186
00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:38.000
He's talking about not something that's going to happen in the distant future,

187
00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:42.000
but something that is right in front of her in the present.

188
00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:48.000
And the thing that is right in front of her in the present is himself.

189
00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:52.000
Here, Martha is saying, yes, one day there's going to be a resurrection.

190
00:13:52.000 --> 00:14:00.000
But what she doesn't realize is that she is standing in the very presence of the one who is the resurrection and is the life.

191
00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:05.000
So he says to her, I am the resurrection and the life.

192
00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:10.000
Whoever believes in me, though he die, yet shall he live.

193
00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:15.000
And everyone who lives and believes in me shall never die.

194
00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:18.000
He's not just talking about a kind of a concept.

195
00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:26.000
He is talking about himself and he is present with her in the midst of her grief.

196
00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:31.000
I saw a clip a few days ago of Tanner from Love on the Spectrum.

197
00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:37.000
He was talking about how much he loves Jack Black and he was being interviewed.

198
00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:44.000
He said, one day I want to meet Jack Black and they played a video of Jack Black giving him a message on the screen.

199
00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:48.000
And as the video is playing, Jack Black runs around the corner.

200
00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:51.000
And Tanner is just absolutely elated to meet Jack Black.

201
00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:53.000
He's just giving him hugs.

202
00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:57.000
So he's thinking about, one day I want to meet him and then he sees this message from him.

203
00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:01.000
And then he realizes, no, he is actually right here beside me.

204
00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:06.000
So here in our text, we see Martha saying, like, yes, there's going to be a resurrection on the last day.

205
00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:12.000
And I hear what you're saying, but Jesus is saying, look, I'm standing right in front of you.

206
00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:15.000
So right the way throughout John's gospel and throughout the ministry of Jesus,

207
00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:19.000
he made it clear that he is the I am.

208
00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:24.000
He is God himself present among us dwelling with us.

209
00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:29.000
He is the source of life. He is the one who has the power of resurrection.

210
00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:34.000
He is the living reality that the truth points to.

211
00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:38.000
And he's about to demonstrate this by raising Lazarus from the dead.

212
00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:42.000
So the truth she needs to see more than anything isn't just an idea.

213
00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:45.000
It is a person and that is Jesus.

214
00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:50.000
So this Easter, we're not just being invited to an idea to just ponder some things.

215
00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:54.000
I hope we all do ponder what Easter is all about.

216
00:15:54.000 --> 00:16:05.000
But ultimately, we're being invited to a living person, Jesus, who is the resurrection and the life.

217
00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:08.000
When everything else gives way, this truth holds.

218
00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:12.000
Jesus is our life.

219
00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:15.000
So he comes not only with truth.

220
00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:19.000
He also comes thirdly with tears.

221
00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:22.000
Jesus doesn't just tell her truth.

222
00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:24.000
We see also Jesus weeping.

223
00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:29.000
In the next scene of the account, Martha's sister Mary comes to see Jesus

224
00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:31.000
and Mary is weeping.

225
00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:34.000
Others around Mary are weeping.

226
00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:38.000
And in her tears, she falls at Jesus' feet.

227
00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:42.000
And she says the exact same words her sister said earlier.

228
00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:49.000
She says, Lord, if you had been here, my brother would not have died.

229
00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:56.000
But although Jesus hears the same statement from her, he doesn't respond in the same way.

230
00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:59.000
He deals with her individually.

231
00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:03.000
What we actually see here is an emotional response from Jesus.

232
00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:08.000
He gives truth to Martha, but he gives tears to Mary.

233
00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:11.000
We read that he is deeply moved and troubled.

234
00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:17.000
And we read these two wonderful words, Jesus wept.

235
00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:19.000
And reading this makes you ponder.

236
00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:26.000
Like, since Jesus knows what he's about to do, why is he crying?

237
00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:29.000
Like, surely he walks up on these people crying and he thinks,

238
00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:34.000
like, if you only knew what I knew, you would be rejoicing right now.

239
00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:38.000
Like, I've got the truth and I'm about to raise lasers from the dead.

240
00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:41.000
If you only knew, you'd be happy like I am happy.

241
00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:43.000
But that's not what Jesus does.

242
00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:45.000
He weeps.

243
00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:47.000
Why?

244
00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:54.000
Because he is a savior who weeps with those who weep.

245
00:17:54.000 --> 00:18:01.000
Jesus loves us so much that he is willing to fully embrace our humanity,

246
00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:10.000
even our sorrows, even if it is but for a moment, he weeps with us in our sadness.

247
00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:14.000
In Isaiah 53, back in the Old Testament, hundreds of years before this,

248
00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:20.000
it told us that the Messiah, the Lord's servant, was one who was a man of sorrows

249
00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:22.000
and acquainted with grief.

250
00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:30.000
He opens up his heart to those who are grieving, even to the point of tears.

251
00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:31.000
Now isn't this interesting?

252
00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:39.000
It tells us that truth doesn't immediately drive tears away.

253
00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:45.000
Here in Jesus, we can see that tears don't necessarily indicate a lack of faith

254
00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:48.000
or spiritual immaturity.

255
00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:54.000
You can believe the truth and grieve your losses.

256
00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:57.000
Both of those things can be true at the same time.

257
00:18:57.000 --> 00:18:59.000
This is what Jesus does.

258
00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:04.000
People think, you know, when it comes to church, you've got to come like pasting a shiny smile on

259
00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:06.000
as though everything was okay.

260
00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:08.000
You've got it all together.

261
00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:09.000
We know the truth.

262
00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:11.000
We know that we'll be with the Lord one day.

263
00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:15.000
We're not touched by any of this sadness.

264
00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:18.000
That's not the example that Jesus gives.

265
00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:25.000
He believes the truth and he weeps with us in our pain.

266
00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:30.000
We know that we're grieving and we can believe.

267
00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:34.000
So why does Jesus weep because he truly loves us?

268
00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:38.000
But you know, sorrow isn't the only emotion he expresses here.

269
00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:43.000
When it says that he was deeply moved, now this is something that like Bible commentators

270
00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:46.000
and scholars really, you know, go back and forth on.

271
00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:50.000
When it says he was deeply moved, that literally conveys anger.

272
00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:54.000
He's angry as he is there near the tomb.

273
00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:58.000
So we might get been out of shape and wonder, well, like, is he sympathizing in sorrow with

274
00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:02.000
our tears or is he angry?

275
00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:06.000
Well, both of those things can be true at the same time as well.

276
00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:10.000
Now, he's not like angry at like Mary for crying.

277
00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:13.000
Like we've already we've already seen that he's weeping with her.

278
00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:18.000
So what is going on here is he can see more than anybody else can see.

279
00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:22.000
He can sympathize with Mary and others who are weeping.

280
00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:26.000
He is sitting with them in their grief and yet he sees the bigger picture.

281
00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:30.000
He sees the devastating effects of sin and unbelief.

282
00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:33.000
He sees the enemy of death.

283
00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:37.000
He sees where all this is heading with his cross.

284
00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:40.000
And he looks at his at this enemy, which is death.

285
00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:45.000
He's he's he's angry.

286
00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:48.000
And in this, we also see that he's not somebody who just feels sadness

287
00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:51.000
and is unable to do something about it.

288
00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:54.000
He sees the worst things you can go through seeing somebody you love suffer

289
00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:57.000
and not being able to do anything about it.

290
00:20:57.000 --> 00:20:59.000
He sees us in our sadness.

291
00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:06.000
He weeps with us, but he's deeply moved and can do something about it.

292
00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:09.000
He can bring transformation.

293
00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:12.000
So he came with tears, but he also came fourthly and lastly

294
00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:16.000
to bring transformation to bring true change.

295
00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:20.000
So Jesus doesn't just comfort us in our grief.

296
00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:25.000
He brings it to our resolve and he brings about the change that is needed.

297
00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:29.000
So in the next scene, Jesus deeply moved comes to the tomb.

298
00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:32.000
He says, take away the stone.

299
00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:35.000
They say, well, Martha says he's been dead for days.

300
00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:38.000
He's going to smell.

301
00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:44.000
She's not fully grasped what he told her earlier about himself that her brother will rise.

302
00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:49.000
He says to her, did I not tell you that if you believed you will see the glory of God?

303
00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:54.000
They roll away the stone from the mouth of the cave that was being used as a tomb.

304
00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:56.000
Then notice what Jesus says.

305
00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:57.000
He says two things.

306
00:21:57.000 --> 00:21:59.000
One is he says a prayer.

307
00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:05.000
He prays and what he prays shows that he had actually already been praying.

308
00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:11.000
Now he's praying aloud in a way that invites people into the reality of what is going on here.

309
00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:13.000
He thanks his father.

310
00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:18.000
He prays that those around him would be brought to faith in him.

311
00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:23.000
He prays in a way that is inviting everybody around him into the life of God,

312
00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:26.000
into this deeper reality that is taking place.

313
00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:32.000
He says this prayer and then he speaks a command.

314
00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:35.000
He says Lazarus with a loud voice.

315
00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:39.000
Lazarus, come forth.

316
00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:40.000
What happens?

317
00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:44.000
Lazarus instantly rises from the dead.

318
00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:48.000
When Jesus speaks, the dead are raised to life.

319
00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:53.000
I've heard it said many times before that if he didn't specify Lazarus,

320
00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:58.000
every single grave would have opened and everybody would have come out.

321
00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:02.000
Here's the thing, if he did it for Lazarus, he can do it for anyone.

322
00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:04.000
Somebody might say, well, I'm not dead yet.

323
00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:05.000
What do you mean?

324
00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:07.000
He can raise me.

325
00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:15.000
Well, Scripture actually teaches that we are dead spiritually before we come to know Jesus.

326
00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:20.000
Death separates us, physical death separates us from life in this world,

327
00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:25.000
but spiritual death separates us from God.

328
00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:29.000
And that is our condition, apart from Christ.

329
00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:34.000
And that will be our condition forever if we die without Christ,

330
00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:42.000
because he is the life, he's the source of life.

331
00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:43.000
Jesus gives eternal life.

332
00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:47.000
We see that here, but we also hear Jesus earlier in the Gospel of John.

333
00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:54.000
Say, truly, truly, I say to you, whoever hears my word, whoever hears my word

334
00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:58.000
and believes him who sent me has eternal life.

335
00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:05.000
So like Lazarus, we are all invited to hear Jesus calling us to come forth.

336
00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:09.000
He says that those who put their faith in him have eternal life,

337
00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:11.000
and this life goes on forever.

338
00:24:11.000 --> 00:24:14.000
So when we face death, it will not be the end.

339
00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:22.000
If our faith has been in Jesus, we will go to be with Christ one day.

340
00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:28.000
When we face death, we will be then welcomed by Jesus.

341
00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:33.000
And faith in Jesus isn't just believing that certain facts about Jesus are true.

342
00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:38.000
Once again, it is coming to the person of Jesus.

343
00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:42.000
But also we know that Jesus will bring about a final resurrection.

344
00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:45.000
In John 5, Jesus said, truly, I say to you, an hour is coming

345
00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:50.000
and is now here when the dead will hear the voice of the Son of God.

346
00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:53.000
And those who hear will live.

347
00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:58.000
So ultimately, Jesus didn't come just to take us out of this broken world.

348
00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:02.000
Right? Our final hope isn't just that we will die and leave this world

349
00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:05.000
and go to be with Jesus somewhere in heaven.

350
00:25:05.000 --> 00:25:14.000
Our ultimate hope is that Jesus has come to restore and to redeem this broken world.

351
00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:17.000
And there's coming a day when one day Jesus will say,

352
00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:21.000
come forth and the dead in Christ will rise.

353
00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:26.000
And everything that is sad will become untrue and every promise will be fulfilled.

354
00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:29.000
And we will live with him forevermore.

355
00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:35.000
The promise is that we will be with Christ forever in a new creation.

356
00:25:35.000 --> 00:25:40.000
We will dwell with him forever in that place without sickness,

357
00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:45.000
without death and all of the brokenness we see and feel.

358
00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:47.000
So his coming may feel delayed.

359
00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:49.000
If that's going to happen when Jesus returns, we might think,

360
00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:52.000
well, it'd be great if he turned up now.

361
00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:57.000
I'm still feeling sickness now or I've gone through this time of grief now.

362
00:25:57.000 --> 00:26:00.000
It'd be great if he turned up. Why does he delay?

363
00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:02.000
Well, Scripture is clear about that.

364
00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:09.000
He delays his coming so that more and more people will come to know him

365
00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:12.000
and have life in him and be with him forevermore.

366
00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:18.000
He's not willing that any should perish but that all should come to repentance.

367
00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:21.000
He delays out of love for us.

368
00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:23.000
So what's the response?

369
00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:24.000
What is our response?

370
00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:30.000
Well, we read later on in John 11 that many people believed in Jesus,

371
00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:32.000
but others went to go speak to the Pharisees

372
00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:36.000
and then this plot was made to put Jesus to death.

373
00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:39.000
And that's what happens. Jesus dies.

374
00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:43.000
He was laid in a tomb and hope seemed to be lost.

375
00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:45.000
There was a delay.

376
00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:47.000
His delay was motivated by love.

377
00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:51.000
Three days later, he rose again from the dead.

378
00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:58.000
Death could not hold the one who is the resurrection and the life.

379
00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:01.000
So how are we responding to the risen Jesus?

380
00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:03.000
How are you responding today?

381
00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:06.000
Jesus asked Martha an important question that we read

382
00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:08.000
and I want to ask you that question.

383
00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:10.000
Do you believe this?

384
00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:14.000
Do you believe that Jesus is the resurrection and the life?

385
00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:19.000
Have you put your faith in Jesus?

386
00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:21.000
Why not reach out the empty hand of faith

387
00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:27.000
to receive the gift of life that he offers you in himself?

388
00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:32.000
The question is also not have we believed in Jesus at some point

389
00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:34.000
but also are we trusting in him now,

390
00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:37.000
even in the midst of our disappointments?

391
00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:39.000
What does faith look like in the midst of grief?

392
00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:42.000
It looks like bringing it to him.

393
00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:45.000
Faith in Jesus doesn't mean that we no longer know

394
00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:47.000
any disappointments in this life

395
00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:50.000
but it does mean that we know where to bring them.

396
00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:52.000
We know where to bring our tears.

397
00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:54.000
We know where to bring our disappointment.

398
00:27:54.000 --> 00:27:56.000
We know where our ultimate hope is found.

399
00:27:56.000 --> 00:27:58.000
It is found in Jesus.

400
00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:01.000
And we can know whatever we're going through

401
00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:05.000
that he loved us enough to suffer for us,

402
00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:07.000
speak the truth to us,

403
00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:09.000
even weep with us

404
00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:11.000
and even die and rise again

405
00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:14.000
that we might have life forevermore.

406
00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:17.000
Let's pray.

407
00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:20.000
Life for us to all just pause in this moment,

408
00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:22.000
take a moment in silence

409
00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:25.000
to personally respond to God in prayer

410
00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:28.000
right where you're sent.

411
00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:46.000
Lord, you are love and you are life.

412
00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:48.000
Lord, I pray that you would help us

413
00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:52.000
to hear your voice calling us to come.

414
00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:54.000
We would trust in you

415
00:28:54.000 --> 00:28:56.000
and we would follow you on this path of life

416
00:28:56.000 --> 00:28:58.000
that you have laid before us.

417
00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:01.000
I pray that you would draw each one of us to yourself.

418
00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:03.000
Lord, for those who doubt,

419
00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:06.000
I pray that you'd give faith.

420
00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:08.000
For those who mourn,

421
00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:11.000
I pray that you would give hope.

422
00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:15.000
Lord, may we all know your love,

423
00:29:15.000 --> 00:29:18.000
an ever-deepening measure.

424
00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:21.000
In Jesus' name, amen.

